        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-secondary">5. Maintain Your Sovereign Power</h1>
        <p class="text-lg italic text-primary/80">"Don't give people too much power over you or you'll be at their mercy"</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        The moment someone else's approval becomes necessary for your peace of mind, you've surrendered your 
        sovereignty. This doesn't mean isolation or selfishness—it means maintaining enough independence that 
        you can make decisions based on wisdom rather than fear. Sovereign power is about having options, 
        maintaining alternatives, and never becoming so dependent on any single person or situation that 
        you lose your ability to choose freely.
      </p>
      
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">The Anatomy of Dependency</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        Dependency comes in many forms: financial, emotional, social, professional, and psychological. Each 
        type of dependency hands control of your life to someone else. Financial dependency means you can't 
        afford to disagree with someone who controls your income. Emotional dependency means you need someone 
        else's approval to feel good about yourself. Social dependency means your identity is tied to a 
        particular group or relationship.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        The insidious nature of dependency is that it often develops gradually. You don't wake up one day 
        completely dependent—you make small compromises, each one seeming reasonable in isolation, until 
        you realize you're trapped in a situation where someone else holds all the cards. By then, the 
        cost of reclaiming your independence feels overwhelming.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-secondary/5 to-primary/5 p-6 rounded-box border border-secondary/20 backdrop-blur-sm mb-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-secondary mb-3">The Five Pillars of Sovereign Power:</h4>
        <ol class="text-base-content/70 text-sm space-y-2">
          <li><strong class="text-secondary">1. Financial Independence:</strong> Multiple income sources, emergency funds, minimal debt</li>
          <li><strong class="text-secondary">2. Emotional Self-Sufficiency:</strong> Internal validation, personal hobbies, individual identity</li>
          <li><strong class="text-secondary">3. Social Diversification:</strong> Varied relationships, multiple friend groups, broad networks</li>
          <li><strong class="text-secondary">4. Professional Optionality:</strong> Marketable skills, industry connections, career alternatives</li>
          <li><strong class="text-secondary">5. Geographic Mobility:</strong> Ability to relocate, minimal location-dependent assets</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">Case Study: The Corporate Executive's Liberation</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        David spent fifteen years climbing the corporate ladder at a major consulting firm. By his late thirties, 
        he was earning a substantial salary, had a company car, stock options, and a prestigious title. On paper, 
        he was successful. In reality, he was completely trapped. His lifestyle required his current income, 
        his skills were highly specialized to his industry, and his identity was entirely wrapped up in his 
        professional status.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Dependency Trap:</strong> When David's company announced layoffs, he realized how vulnerable 
        he was. His mortgage, car payments, and lifestyle expenses consumed 95% of his income. He had no savings 
        because he'd been living paycheck-to-paycheck despite the large paycheck. His skills were so specialized 
        that finding equivalent work would be difficult. Worse, his self-worth was so tied to his job title 
        that the prospect of "starting over" felt devastating.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Sovereignty Strategy:</strong> David began systematically reducing his dependencies. He 
        downsized his home, sold the expensive car, and cut lifestyle expenses by 50%. He used the extra money 
        to build an emergency fund equal to one year of expenses. He started a consulting side business to 
        diversify his income and develop broader skills. Most importantly, he began deriving identity and 
        satisfaction from activities outside work—coaching youth soccer, learning photography, building 
        relationships with people who didn't know or care about his job title.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Liberation:</strong> When David's position was eventually eliminated two years later, 
        he was prepared. Instead of panic, he felt excitement about new possibilities. His emergency fund 
        gave him time to be selective about his next role. His side business provided immediate income. 
        His diversified identity meant losing his job was disappointing but not devastating. He ultimately 
        took a role that paid 20% less but offered better work-life balance—a choice he could only make 
        because he'd reclaimed his sovereignty.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">Financial Sovereignty: Beyond Basic Security</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        Financial independence isn't just about having money—it's about having options. The goal isn't 
        necessarily to become wealthy, but to reach a point where financial considerations don't control 
        your major life decisions. This means different things at different income levels, but the principles 
        remain consistent.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>Emergency Fund Strategy:</strong> Most financial advisors recommend 3-6 months of expenses 
        in emergency savings. For sovereignty purposes, consider this the bare minimum. True financial 
        sovereignty often requires 12-24 months of expenses saved, giving you the freedom to leave bad 
        situations, take calculated risks, or weather extended difficulties.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-secondary/5 to-base-200/50 p-4 rounded-box border border-secondary/15">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-secondary mb-2">Signs of Lost Sovereignty</h4>
          <ul class="text-base-content/70 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>• Can't afford to disagree with someone</li>
            <li>• Need others' approval to feel good</li>
            <li>• Can't leave a bad situation</li>
            <li>• Identity tied to single role/relationship</li>
            <li>• Fear making independent decisions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-secondary/5 to-base-200/50 p-4 rounded-box border border-secondary/15">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-secondary mb-2">Signs of Healthy Sovereignty</h4>
          <ul class="text-base-content/70 text-sm space-y-1">
            <li>• Can walk away from bad situations</li>
            <li>• Make decisions based on values</li>
            <li>• Multiple sources of fulfillment</li>
            <li>• Financial breathing room</li>
            <li>• Strong individual identity</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

